<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Henry, Alexander. Travels in the Red River Department (Abridged), 1806. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0024</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">6</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;"><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">and in some places mixed with stones<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  At 9 A.M. we passed among the sandy hills, from the summit of which we could see the Turtle Mountain<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Soon after we fell upon the Assiniboine <span style="text-decoration:underline;">route</span> to Montagne a La Bosse.  The heat of the weather was intolerable &#8212; fortunately for us that water was <span class="AddHand-author">found</span> in every little hollow from the rain of the preceeding night.  In dry seasons travelling in these extensive plains is dangerous for many people have died of drouth in this quarter<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Passed several Assiniboine Campments of this summer these people are remarkable for choosing delightful spots for their <span class="AddHand-author">Tents</span> whence they can command an extended view of the Country around.  Crossed the River and continued until late whence we stopped for the night upon the top of a beautiful high hill<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  A fine breeze from the NW. kept down the musquitoes and rendered ou<span class="AddHand-author">r</span> Situation delightful.  Here we could see Buffaloes in great abundance.  This being the rutting season they kept bellowing all night and several droves passed near our Camp.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Wednesday 16 </p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">At Day break our horses were saddled when I came to mount I found my seat very uncomfortable having a blister of the size of an Egg under each thigh occassioned by the excessive heat of yesterday and the continued friction of my leather trowsers and saddle<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  However I continued came to another little River which runs out of the Tete la B<span class="AddHand-author">i</span>che Mountain<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  <span class="AddHand-editors">[L]</span>eaving this river we went southerly across a plain.  Plenty of Buffaloes chased and killed</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">one</p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[10]</span></p>

